WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.500
Hi everyone, my name is Isabella Velasquez and welcome to the end-to-end workflow with Positeam.

00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:10.500
Let's say you have a dataset that's updated regularly. You created an awesome Shiny app for it,

00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:16.500
and you want your app to pull in the most up-to-date data without constantly reloading it unless it has changed.

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:21.000
Today, we'll explore one workflow option using Positeam and Pins.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Pins provide a straightforward way to store and share datasets as files.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.000
They are ideal for lightweight use cases where you don't need the overhead of a full relational or NoSQL database.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
You can save objects like data frames, models, and plots, and load them easily using PinRead or PinReactiveRead,

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
making the process less complex for small to medium-sized projects.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.500
They are well-supported in Shiny applications, making it easy to work with pinned data reactively.

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:53.000
So, you can pull and refresh data as needed with minimal code changes.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.500
Today, you'll see how to simplify your process for keeping dynamic data current,

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:01.000
and how to reflect those changes in your app or dashboard.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.000
With that, let's get started.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
So, let's talk about some key tools and concepts for today.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.500
Today's project is a Shiny app that I built to streamline our marketing content calendar.

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:20.000
I rely on Jira for managing deadlines, but its interface isn't the easiest for quickly scanning dates across categories.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:28.000
With Shiny, I could create a responsive and user-friendly interface that makes it easier to track, filter, and visualize the schedule.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.000
And through the use of the tools we'll talk about today, I know it's always showing the most updated Jira data.

00:01:36.500 --> 00:01:42.500
To run this workflow, we start by retrieving the desired Jira data through its API.

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:49.500
Using Posit Workbench, we create a document called data-pull.qmd to pull and clean the data.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.500
Next, we connect to our Posit Connect pin board and write the clean data to a pin.

00:01:55.500 --> 00:01:59.500
This process can be scheduled to run automatically.

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:07.500
Then, we develop our Shiny app in app.R, also within Posit Workbench, and deploy it to Posit Connect.

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:16.500
By using pin read-reactive, the Shiny app will automatically update whenever the text changes in the pin on Posit Connect.

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:24.500
I used a Cordo document to pull data because it allows combining both Python and R chunks.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:28.500
However, this process could be handled with just a script.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:36.500
First, we write code to request data from the API, converting it into a usable format like a data frame.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:40.500
After that, we clean the raw data for analysis.

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:50.500
But given that Jira data constantly updates, the challenge is creating a clean dataset that's easy to access and keeps up with changes.

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:52.500
So how can we do this?

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:55.500
Enter pins.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:59.500
Pins enables you to store and retrieve the processed data.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:07.500
In the data-pull.qmd file, we include the script to connect to our board, in this case Posit Connect,

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:12.500
clean the data, and then write the clean data into a pin.

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:19.500
The pin is stored on our board and can be easily referenced in scripts or Shiny apps for data access and use.

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:30.500
So in this case, in the data-pull.qmd file, we have in a code chunk the connection to the board.

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:35.500
After that, we can pull the data and clean it as needed.

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:40.500
Then finally, we write the pin to our board using pin write.

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:47.500
And wherever we want to access it, then we would use pin read in that script or that app.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:59.500
And so to keep that pin up to date, we can schedule automatically refreshes of the pin with Posit Connect.

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:08.500
So here I go into the settings, go to schedule, and then select the options that I want for rerunning the output.

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:17.500
That way, I make sure anytime the pin is accessed, it's always using the most up-to-date data since the last refresh.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:24.500
So we've talked about various different outputs that you could put in Connect.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:27.500
So pins and another is Shiny.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.500
So what exactly is Shiny?

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:35.500
Shiny is a framework for creating web applications using R or Python.

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:40.500
And the web apps respond to user inputs and data changes in real time.

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:45.500
So you can change your analyses into interactive applications.

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:54.500
Its power lies in reactivity, where outputs instantly update whenever inputs or underlying data change.

00:04:54.500 --> 00:05:03.500
This allows the app to stay responsive and interactive without needing manual refreshes, making it perfect for real-time data exploration.

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:08.500
So how exactly can we do this in Shiny with data?

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:14.500
We can use pin reactive read from the pins package.

00:05:14.500 --> 00:05:20.500
Using pin reactive read in our Shiny app enables real-time access to the pin data.

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:30.500
This function automatically updates the app whenever the pin is refreshed, ensuring that the app stays responsive and always uses the latest data available.

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:33.500
So let's see it in action.

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:35.500
This is my Jira board.

00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:40.500
It contains the data that I want to recreate in my Shiny app.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:46.500
So you can see there are a variety of tasks such as blog posts and social posts.

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:51.500
I have them categorized into different topics like tidy models and Shiny.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:55.500
If I click into one, you can actually see the due date.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:59.500
So that's what I want to represent on my calendar.

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:09.500
And of course, I want my calendar to reflect whatever information is on this board at any point in time so that I can make sure that it is up to date.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:13.500
So to do that, let's go into Posit Team.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:15.500
This is our home page.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:18.500
Posit Team is made up of three products.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:20.500
Posit Workbench for development.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:24.500
Posit Package Manager for exactly that, managing packages.

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:32.500
And Posit Connect for deploying and publishing apps, documents, pins, all sorts of data outputs.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:36.500
Since we want to develop something, we're going to enter Posit Workbench.

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:41.500
From here, we're going to create a new session for RStudio Pro.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:53.500
As you can see, Posit Workbench offers a bunch of other different configuration options like connecting to Databricks or Snowflake, different images and resources.

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:55.500
But this is good for now.

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:59.500
I'm going to start the session and it will automatically let me in once it's ready.

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:16.500
So my project is in the Shiny Calendar folder.

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:18.500
I'm going to open it up.

00:07:30.500 --> 00:07:34.500
Here are the files I need to create my calendar.

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:40.500
And so, first, here's the data-pull.porto document.

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:47.500
As mentioned earlier, I chose the porto document so I can mix R and Python code chunks.

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.500
However, that's not necessary.

00:07:49.500 --> 00:08:00.500
As you can imagine, porto can run in either language or you could also do this process through an R or Python script.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:05.500
But this is how I like to do it based on my own personal preference.

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:13.500
To walk through it, first code chunk is the setup code chunk where I list all the R packages that I'm going to use.

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:24.500
And then I have the Jira API key, which actually lets me access data from my Jira board and pull it into Posit Workbench.

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:30.500
And then I'm also going to configure my pin board, in this case, Posit Connect,

00:08:30.500 --> 00:08:40.500
by specifying the Posit Connect server that I'm going to use and providing the API key since Posit Connect is a secure server.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:43.500
Next, I have my Python chunk.

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:48.500
So again, there's no real reason for this other than my own preference.

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:58.500
When I first wrote this function out, I wrote it in Python and I didn't want to translate it into R, but it's absolutely possible to do so.

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:08.500
And so one neat thing about using both R and Python chunks, using the package reticulate,

00:09:08.500 --> 00:09:15.500
I can actually call objects from across different programming languages within the same document.

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:24.500
So if you recall earlier, I noted the Jira API key that I needed to actually use to access the API.

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:31.500
And here in this Python chunk, I'm referring to it by specifying R.API key.

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:37.500
So what that's saying is look at the R environment and pull the API key.

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:43.500
Next, I have the two URLs that I'm going to be using for pulling the data.

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:49.500
So there are probably many different ways of doing this, but in this example, I just have two separate URLs,

00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:55.500
one for the social post and one for the blog post, and I'll run the same functions of both.

00:09:55.500 --> 00:10:03.500
Again, it's just my personal preference and maybe more efficient ways of doing this.

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:09.500
Next is the function for getting the response from the URL.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:15.500
So pulling in that data and which results in a JSON file.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:25.500
And for the social post and the blog post, they're going to be saved in these objects called social results and blog results in the Python environment.

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:33.500
However, R is my language of choice, and so I'd like to port this back into R and work with it from there.

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:39.500
So back in an R chunk, I create another function called results,

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:48.500
which takes that data from the response in the Python chunk as a category and then does a series of data cleaning steps.

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:56.500
So first thing it does is it transports it into a table so I can run my usual R operations on it.

00:10:56.500 --> 00:11:06.500
I do things like add the due date for that particular task and convert it into an actual date with LuverDate.

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:19.500
I add a column for status, a column for the different labels, and then another column for the URL for that particular task so I can refer to it on the actual board if I so choose.

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:27.500
And then use dplyr's bind columns in order to bring all of those different pieces of information together.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:33.500
And then I run that function on both the social results and the blog results.

00:11:33.500 --> 00:11:39.500
And again, I am referring to something from a Python chunk by using pi and dollar sign,

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:45.500
and then also adding the name of the category, either social or blog, next to it.

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:53.500
And finally, I have another code chunk that goes through, binds those two tables together,

00:11:53.500 --> 00:12:00.500
and then creates a series of columns that I'm going to need for creating the calendar.

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:06.500
So the calendar in Shiny is going to be created using a really awesome package called Toast UI,

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:10.500
which has a variety of widgets, including a calendar one.

00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:16.500
And the data needs to be configured in a certain way in order for it to look the way that you would like.

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:23.500
So things like adding colors to the different labels and things like that.

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:28.500
You could do that in the data frame and then Toast UI's calendar will be able to read into it.

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:39.500
But now that I have this all results table that has all of my API data that I want to showcase cleaned up

00:12:39.500 --> 00:12:44.500
and associated with different requirements for the calendar,

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:50.500
now I can actually write that clean data onto my PositConnect board.

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:57.500
So here I refer to the board from up above, I let it know which data it is that I want to pin,

00:12:57.500 --> 00:13:02.500
and then the name of the pin so that I can refer to it later.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:08.500
And so if I render this, see what it looks like.

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:21.500
And it looks just like a regular rendered quarter document.

00:13:21.500 --> 00:13:26.500
I didn't have any comments or markdown in it at all.

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:35.500
But remember, every single time that this QMD file is run, the JIRA data from the board is pulled,

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:38.500
it's cleaned up and then written to that pin.

00:13:38.500 --> 00:13:45.500
So that means that pin will have the latest data as of the last time that this document was run.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:53.500
So what if I want the latest data without having to manually run this QMD file myself?

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:57.500
And that's where we can deploy to PositConnect.

00:13:57.500 --> 00:14:00.500
So there are a variety of ways of deploying to PositConnect.

00:14:00.500 --> 00:14:02.500
You can do get back deployment.

00:14:02.500 --> 00:14:08.500
So anytime it senses a change in a GitHub repository, it will re-render on PositConnect.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:10.500
You could do it through the command line interface.

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:14.500
But I'm going to show you how to do it through push button deployment.

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:19.500
So if I click this blue button, I have actually deployed this quarter document before.

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:23.500
So it automatically pulled in the information that it needs.

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:27.500
So I'm going to hit publish.

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:33.500
And down here, it's going to, as you can imagine, create the environment that it needs,

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:40.500
re-render the quarter document and everything in order to deploy it to PositConnect.

00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:09.500
So here's that same render file, but now it is on PositConnect.

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:18.500
So the key part here is the configuration options that PositConnect allows you to have for your data content.

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:23.500
So you can do things like allow sharing with other folks.

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:27.500
You can add vanity URLs.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:33.500
So like, let's say, file, data, pull.

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:35.500
Something like that.

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:36.500
Save it.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:39.500
And I can share this URL with other folks.

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:45.500
And then most critically for today, I can schedule the output for refresh.

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:52.500
And so that every time that the document is refreshed, that pin is overridden with the latest data

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:56.500
and can be used in other places like a Shiny app.

00:15:56.500 --> 00:16:01.500
And in terms of the configuration for the schedule, I can specify other time zones.

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:06.500
I can say, let's do it at 6.55 in the morning rather than 7.

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:11.500
Run every day, every two days, et cetera.

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:15.500
So I'm going to save this for here.

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:22.500
So just once again, every single day at 6.55 in the morning, this document will be run,

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:27.500
the pin will be rewritten, and it will have the latest data as of that time.

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:32.500
And I could make it more often if I want to, but let's say I just look at the calendar once a day,

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:35.500
so that's good enough for me.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:40.500
So now that I have done this, now I want to actually use that pin for something.

00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:45.500
So let's return to Posit Workbench.

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:49.500
And now I'm going to open up my app.r file.

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:58.500
So app.r contains the Shiny app that builds the calendar using the data that we just pinned.

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:04.500
We begin with the packages that we're going to need to actually build the Shiny app.

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:07.500
And similarly, we're going to configure our board.

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:12.500
So we're going to connect to our Posit Connect board with our Posit Connect API key.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:19.500
And then I'm going to specify the name of the pin that I want to use for this app.

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:24.500
Another package that I wanted to call out is BS Lib.

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:31.500
So BS Lib offers extensive customization, layouts, theming for your Shiny apps.

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:37.500
One example is the ability to pull in Google fonts very easily, as you can see here.

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:40.500
Other things you can do is say I want a footer.

